Analyze Mobile RAT Using MobSF
Objectives
By the end of this lab, students will be able to:

Install and configure Mobile Security Framework (MobSF) for Android malware analysis
Perform static analysis of mobile RAT applications using MobSF
Identify malicious permissions, components, and communication patterns in RAT samples
Automate RAT detection using MobSF's REST API with Python
Generate security assessment reports for mobile malware
Prerequisites
Before starting this lab, students should have:

Basic understanding of Android application structure (APK files, permissions, components)
Familiarity with Linux command line operations
Basic Python programming knowledge
Understanding of REST APIs and JSON data formats
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides pre-configured Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Click Start Lab to access your dedicated environment with MobSF pre-installed and sample RAT APKs ready for analysis.

Environment Details:

MobSF server accessible at http://localhost:8000
Sample RAT APKs located in /home/student/samples/
Python 3.8+ with required libraries pre-installed
Task 1: Configure MobSF and Upload RAT Sample
Step 1.1: Verify MobSF Installation
Check that MobSF is properly installed and configured:

# Navigate to MobSF directory
cd /opt/Mobile-Security-Framework-MobSF

# Verify installation
ls -la

# Check Python dependencies
pip3 list | grep -E "django|requests|lxml"
Step 1.2: Start MobSF Server
Launch the MobSF web interface:

# Start MobSF server (runs on port 8000)
cd /opt/Mobile-Security-Framework-MobSF
python3 manage.py runserver 0.0.0.0:8000
Note: Keep this terminal open. Open a new terminal for subsequent commands.

Step 1.3: Access MobSF Web Interface
Open Firefox browser and navigate to:

http://localhost:8000
You should see the MobSF dashboard with an upload interface.

Step 1.4: Upload Sample RAT APK
Locate the sample RAT APK:
# List available samples
ls -lh /home/student/samples/
In the MobSF web interface:
Click Upload & Analyze
Select /home/student/samples/android-rat-sample.apk
Click Analyze
Wait 2-3 minutes for static analysis to complete
Step 1.5: Review Analysis Dashboard
Once analysis completes, examine these key sections:

App Information: Package name, version, target SDK
Security Score: Overall risk assessment
Permissions: Requested permissions with risk levels
Components: Activities, services, receivers, providers
Code Analysis: Security issues and vulnerabilities
Task 2: Analyze RAT Characteristics and Behavior
Step 2.1: Examine Dangerous Permissions
Review the permissions section and identify RAT-specific indicators:

High-Risk Permissions for RATs:

CAMERA - Remote surveillance capability
RECORD_AUDIO - Audio monitoring
ACCESS_FINE_LOCATION - Location tracking
READ_SMS / SEND_SMS - SMS interception/sending
CALL_PHONE - Phone call control
READ_CONTACTS - Contact list exfiltration
SYSTEM_ALERT_WINDOW - Overlay attacks
DEVICE_ADMIN - Device control
Task: Document which dangerous permissions are present in your sample.

Step 2.2: Analyze Application Components
Examine suspicious components that indicate RAT functionality:

# Create analysis workspace
mkdir -p ~/rat-analysis
cd ~/rat-analysis

# Create component analysis notes file
nano component_analysis.txt
Look for:

Services with names containing: "remote", "control", "admin", "device"
Receivers listening for: BOOT_COMPLETED, SMS_RECEIVED, PHONE_STATE
Activities with admin or accessibility features
Step 2.3: Review Network Security Issues
In the MobSF report, navigate to Network Security section:

Check for cleartext traffic allowances
Identify hardcoded URLs or IP addresses
Look for non-standard ports (not 80, 443, 8080)
Note any suspicious domains or URL shorteners
Step 2.4: Examine Code Analysis Findings
Review the Code Analysis section for:

Obfuscation techniques
Dynamic code loading
Reflection usage
Native code execution
Cryptographic operations
Task: Create a summary of top 5 security issues found.

